line by line,
.asciz "ddbw"   allocates memory with null terminator and ddbw

num 1 and 2 are both long datatypes containing 2 and -5 respectively.

lea stands for load effective address, this one is basically making
%rdi point to the first letter of the memory block we just assigned.

movl copies num1 into eax
movl is used again to copy num2 into ecx

we add with addl, which is 2 + -5 = -3
now this information is stored in eax.

movb al bl 
this one moves the lowest 8 bits of eax (named eax)
into bl register. bl now holds value -3

movzbq (%rdi), %rax
this looks at the mem address held in rdi,
grabs the 8bits(1byte) stored in there
pads the rest of the 64 bits in rax with 0s
and stores it in there.

testb is a logical AND 
we perform this on al itself, meaning that
nothing changes, but the zero flag is set.

je
means jump if equal 
the zero flag was just set, meaning that we jump to 
decrypt_done

subb 
subtract byte. this is the actual decrypting.
uses the key (bl, -3)
to subtract from the ASCII charaters.

so we do - -3, meaning we add three.
this shifts the letters 3 up, 
meaning that the decypted from ddbw is ggez (haha)
HOWEVER, this enire thing is not computed all at once since we 
only grabed one letter at a time. we must continue the loop.

movb %al, (%rdi)
moves the decrypted charater into its corresponding encrypted characters space

inc just increments to that we point to the next character.

jmp decrypt_loop
unconditional jump. we go back into the decrypting loop to process the next characters
until we hit the null terminator.


for decrypt done:
lea ciphertext(%rip), %rdi
resets rdi register to point back to the beggining
meaning that we now can read the entire decryption of ggez in rdi.

call puts(?)
had to search. this is a standard C function that looks at the address and 
prints the string onto the terminal.

movl $0, %eax
set return value to 0, meaning program succecfully executed

ret
returns, and exits the program!

--------afterthoughts----------
I had to learn a few things here like 
lea, puts, and what movzbq actually did. 
I had a good time with this one because I knew that the decrypting wouldnt be anything beyond shift (ceasar in this case) cypher.
I had my hands on a tiny, tiny amount of cryptography from one of the GE classes here.
I almost got tripped up by the simple math of - -3, but then the decrypted characters didnt seem right
was scrating my head at it for a while when ggez (the decrypted) seemed like a much more plausible answer,
so I meticulously looked back to where I was making the mistake! 
fun exercise this one was, much faster than tying to code up the bitwise operations @.@ 

